sec.p:
As shown intable 8, the conjecture that market volatility and dispersion in forecasts covary does not seem to be supported by the data. Although the volatility and dispersion have a positive correlation, the volatility does not Granger‐cause the dispersion and the dispersion does not Granger‐cause the volatility, either. Furthermore, the current volatility can explain only about 3% of the movements of the dispersion while its coefficient is statistically significant. The value of
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\overline{R}^{2}$ \end{document}
               decreases when lagged and future market volatility are included in the regression equation. Therefore, the conjecture that the dispersion may reflect the volatility in the market cannot be accepted at this stage.

Table 9presents the relation between the detrended trading volume and the dispersion. Although the detrended trading volume and dispersion have a positive correlation, the Granger causality tests indicate that neither variable Granger‐causes the other in both directions. Further, the current trading volume can explain only about 2% of the movements of the dispersion while its coefficient is marginally significant. The strong relation between the trading volume and the dispersion in forecasts for individual firms does not seem to be strongly supported by the aggregate data. Table 9
